00:51.938 --> 01:13.738
professors or to see my academic advisor or to see a 
dean or an associate dean even before I became

00:51.938 --> 01:13.738
student body president that I was ever denied. And 
it just wasn't a problem. Now my perception was

01:17.361 --> 01:21.945
that A&M was working then to be inclusive not to 
divide up into special categories. Like I've said

01:27.683 --> 01:38.779
to people, and tell me if you agree or disagree, 
I've said to people, the real important thing was

01:27.683 --> 01:38.779
not what someone's ancestry was, but were you a 
part of A&M?

01:41.383 --> 01:49.755
I had the impression that Jewish kids, Hispanic 
kids, Lebanese kids, in terms of parentage, all

01:41.383 --> 01:49.755
felt part of the group. I'll

01:52.216 --> 01:56.301
say yes and no. And the reason I'll say yes and no is 
sort of the fog. You'll have to reel back, I think,

01:59.044 --> 02:07.454
about 8 to 10 years before 1976. And so let's talk 
about when I may be 10 years, maybe less than that,

02:07.674 --> 02:16.545
about 68, that time frame. Texas had just gone 
through, during that time frame, from 65 to 70. and

02:22.726 --> 02:30.556
even as late as 71 in some instances, forced 
desegregation.

02:30.576 --> 02:46.936
And particularly in towns where there were large 
minority populations, and that generally is the

02:30.576 --> 02:46.936
case as it remains today, sort of like east of 
Interstate 35,

02:30.576 --> 02:46.936
you had had some changes that had taken place. And 
so these are the kinds of kids, now that you've got

02:46.956 --> 02:52.243
at the university environment,

02:53.101 --> 03:08.243
I've always made an argument that supported the 
argument that

02:53.101 --> 03:08.243
kids were ready to make the join the, uh, maybe not 
some of the parents. And so these are the type of

03:08.263 --> 03:15.514
kids that you end up having, but they're mixed in 
with kids from the other part of the state. The

03:15.554 --> 03:18.298
western half of the state where mixed race 
populations are not as great. You've got these

03:21.192 --> 03:26.858
sort of new experiences going on.

03:26.878 --> 03:47.678
Notwithstanding the collectivism that took 
place as a result of the Civil Rights Movement, by

03:26.878 --> 03:47.678
the time you got to about 74, 75,

03:26.878 --> 03:47.678
there was a change, in my view, on the part of that 
population that was beginning to move back into a

03:48.063 --> 04:00.898
separatist, separateness,

03:48.063 --> 04:00.898
looking for an identity, if you will. And so when 
you got, you know, everybody who was just amongst

04:02.120 --> 04:11.471
blacks, for example, there was this thing called 
the Black Awareness Committee. The primary

04:11.491 --> 04:15.015
purpose of the Black Awareness Committee was for 
the purpose of bringing maybe once a year,

04:17.105 --> 04:26.300
somebody who was a prominent black political 
leader or writer or author or whatever to campus

04:17.105 --> 04:26.300
for an event. But the Black Awareness Committee 
also became a social

04:27.542 --> 04:34.493
organization. It also became an activist

04:35.394 --> 04:41.644
organization. in the sense of if there were issues 
that the Black Awareness Committee thought

04:42.029 --> 04:57.969
needed to be brought to the attention of the 
administration, that a lot of these ideas, if any,

04:42.029 --> 04:57.969
flowed from that group.

05:03.335 --> 05:11.125
And it wasn't necessarily, I'm trying to think of 
some issues, but it wasn't necessarily because

05:03.335 --> 05:11.125
people had been denied things. or that people 
thought that they were

05:11.493 --> 05:18.401
being discriminated against. It was more along 
the lines of, you know, we need to have more

05:18.421 --> 05:23.307
opportunities to do this, so help us do that. And so 
that sort of became, that was sort of the

05:23.327 --> 05:32.898
beginning, I think, of sort of the move back to 
divisiveness. It wasn't necessarily promoted by

05:32.918 --> 05:40.707
the university, but it was more promoted by what I 
saw happening sociologically during that time

05:32.918 --> 05:40.707
frame. Well, I think we have it now, today. I think a 
great deal of it today. And it's sort of matured in

05:45.961 --> 05:49.267
the 80s. And so, what had been a forced, what had 
started out as we've been discriminated against,

05:51.551 --> 06:00.487
separate but equal, doesn't work, and all that 
kind of stuff. And the courts say, okay, we're

06:00.507 --> 06:04.855
gonna force you to be equal and we're gonna lump you 
all together. and everybody's going to get along,

06:05.425 --> 06:09.651
and everybody's going to figure out whose badges 
they're going to use, and all this kind of stuff.

06:09.992 --> 06:15.100
When we start getting toward the mid-'70s and 
late-'70s, the war was over. So the draft was gone.

06:18.926 --> 06:29.762
So these other types of things that generally can 
sap the emotions and the thought processes of

06:18.926 --> 06:29.762
people. That distraction wasn't there anymore. 
